Dame Street hasn't changed much since the early 1900s (that's Trinity College at the end). Aside from brighter lights, it's pretty much the same.
To one side of the apartment is Parliament Street, which runs from City Hall to the River.
On the street outside the apartment building, you're looking at Christ Church Cathedral.
Adjacent to the building is Parliament Street...
The many side streets off Dame Street take you to all other main parts of the city.
...which boasts the finest example of Romantic Italianate architecture in Dublin.
Some of the best cafes in Dublin are within minutes of the apartment.
Possibly the very best of all is directly below the apartment!
Some of the Dublin's favourite pubs are within a couple of minute's walk from the apartment.
And that's important when you're visiting Dublin!
The apartment's nearest neighbour is Dublin Castle.
...which was historically the very centre of Dublin City.
You can take a guided tour inside the Castle's buildings.
The garden of Dublin Castle is one of the city's best-kept secrets.
Next door to Dublin Castle - and also directly opposite the apartment - is City Hall.
It has a really spectacular interior, and also offers guided tours.
At the top of Dame Street - and just 1 minute from the apartment - is Christ Church Cathedral.
You can visit and just have a look - or take a tour (including Dublinia).
St Patrick's Cathedral is a 5 minute walk from the apartment - or 3 if you're Swift.
Trinity College Dublin is at the other end of Dame Street, just 3 minutes walk from the apartment.
Trinity College's campus boasts some of Dublin's finest architecture.
Temple Bar still has its old medieval feel to it, with narrow streets, cobblestones and dark arches.
It looks pretty good at night, too.
Temple Bar - Dublin's Cultural Quarter - is a 2 minute walk from the apartment.
Another of the superb stalls in the Temple Bar Food Market.
But Temple Bar's not just about bars and cafes...
The weekly Food Market (every Saturday) is well worth a visit.
The Olympia Theatre on Dame Street is less than a minute from the apartment.
Inside the Olympia Theatre - well worth a visit.
About 3 minutes from the apartment, the Ha'penny Bridge leads to the north side of Dublin city.
Take the Ha'penny Bridge to the Liffey Boardwalk, where you can stroll the length of the river.
The sunsets over the river are spectacular.
Dublin Castle (directly opposite the apartment), as seen from above.

6494825: The dining area looks out over Exchequer St and the book shelves are lined with lots of great books about the city. Our chandelier was made by a friend in New Zealand.
The apartment has an enormous open-plan living space encompassing a kitchen, dining area and sitting room.
Our mid-century Danish dining table seats 6 and if you're too exhausted to cook grab some take-out from the wonderful food hall across the road.
Our bespoke blue kitchen was built and designed by our friend Patrick who built everything else in the apartment as well.
The kitchen is fully equipped with a gas hob, oven, microwave, dishwasher and everything else you might need.
All our storage is cleverly concealed in this blue spine that runs through the middle of the apartment.

The living area leads out onto a large balcony with views across the rooftops. We have a TV with lots of channels and a DVD player with a selection of movies if you're having a night off from Dublin's nightlife.
The built-in desk and bright red Eames office chair make a great  space for work  and of course we have wifi.
The sitting room has an open fire and lots of great original art works by local artists.
The L-shaped sofa converts in seconds to a super-comfortable double bed. We searched for ages to find the best sofa bed on the market and we're pretty confidant you'll be impressed.

The bedroom is situated at the back of the building and it's sound-proofed to ensure you get a quiet night's sleep. The bedroom is somewhat unique with a double queen sized bed in the main part of the room and a set of double bunkbeds built into an alcove at the rear of the room.
Grayson Perry is one of our favourite artists and we picked up this brilliant piece printed on silk at one of his recent exhibitions in Sydney.
The bedroom also has a bunk bed and access to the balcony.
The bespoke bunks are double-width and have concealed lighting. They also come with mattress toppers for extra comfort.
We love these great tiles which we brought over from London. The bathroom also features a bath and a pretty powerful 'rain' shower.
There's lots of extra towels in the hot press and some storage concealed behind the mirrors.
We have installed underfloor heating in the bathroom along with a heated towel rack and a sound-proofed shower so you don't wake up anyone else in the apartment when you're having a scrub.
Here's the sofa-bed set up as a bed. It literally takes about 25 seconds to assemble and we have also provided a mattress topper to ensure you are comfortable.
Two people fit comfortably in the sofa-bed.

The beautiful red brick Victorian building that houses our apartment dates from 1876.
The apartment is on Exchequer St which has lots of other great streets nearby full of restaurants, cafés, bars and of course shops.

The apartment is on the second floor, our windows are directly above the cyclist in this photo. There's a supermarket next door (Dunnes Stores) that stays open late where you can pick up anything you might need.
This is the view from the front of the apartment overlooking Exchequer St and Fallon & Byrne, a wonderful food market and restaurant complex.
The balcony at the rear of the building looks out across the rooftops of this part of the city.
Fallon & Byrne is arguably the best food store in Ireland and luckily it's right across the road. They have a great wine bar in the basement and a wonderful restaurant on the first floor.
The Stag's Head is just down the street from the apartment, it's one of Dublin's best known pubs and definitely worth a visit.
Here's our secret Drinks Cabinet, cleverly concealed within the wall dividing the living and dining areas.
We have lots of games, jigsaws and toys for younger children and even two micro scooters if your kids need to burn off some energy.
An artist friend in Australia painted all these wonderful feet which hang in the sitting room.
This giant photo hangs over the fireplace in the sitting room, it's by a local Dublin artist.

Portobello is a hive for street art. Peter's Place, Richmond Street South (pictured) and Liberty Lane are the best spots for graffiti in Portobello.
Brunch at The Cake Cafe, which is out the back of The Last Bookshop. The outdoor area of the cafe is a beauty and worth visiting for that alone.
Bertie the bookshop dog! A cutie patootie.
Great coffee and organic wine place that's just 30 seconds across the road from our apartment.
Great smash burger place nearby. Does takeaway, also does really good Jalapeño poppers.
A vintage style grocery shop that sells specialty bits.
Inseratsbild 32
Grove Road - a local favourite serving great roadside views on barstools, along with tasty brunch all day. Avo smash, bacon sambos... Tea, coffee... And all that good stuff.
Brother Hubbard South is a much loved neighbourhood joint, focused on Moroccan brunch and speciality coffee.
Locks Windsor Terrace is a stellar restaurant and luckily just a two minute walk away.
A bucket list spot for vegans.
Delish fried chicken sandwiches from Mad Egg off Camden street. They have sticky honey, Buffalo & Ranch, lemon & herb... Not to mention their DIY cheesecake.
Great for healthy but hearty lunch. Can cycle there within 5 mins. Also near to Guinness Storehouse, St. Patrick's Cathedral and Dublinia.
The best Spanish tapas restaurant in Dublin.  Hands down.

Trendy smokehouse with new flavours over a live fire. On the menu: miso and brown butter roasties, wagyu steak, pork tomahawk, skate with dashi, smoked angus, whole brill and langoustine... And more. Walk ins only. Order more than you think you need.
Reasonable prices, great cocktails. Best part is the vibe, the views and the outdoor rooftop terrace.
Really tasty pasta at Sprezzatura, packed with flavour! I recommend ordering two dishes for yourself and sharing a third.

Anyone will tell you that Bunsen makes the best burger in Ireland. Their menu only has two types of burger: single or double - with classic toppings only. This branch is on Wexford Street, but they have other locations around the city.

Bonsai is run by celeb chef, Dylan McGrath. If you're looking for upscale sushi, this is your place. Great ramen can be found back in Portobello's Zakura restaurant and at Yamamori (also try the torched scallop nigiri at their Izakaya + Sake branch).
This is the restaurant that prince Harry and Meghan Markle dined at, during their visit to Ireland.
Hatch and Sons serve authentic Irish stews, blaa sandwiches, skillet breakfasts, soda bread and other delicacies! The Hairy Lemon is also a great place to grab traditional Irish food.

Pickle is a multi-award winning restaurant that plates up sophisticated, North Indian cuisine. It's in a contemporary & casual space decorated with Bollywood posters. On the menu, you can choose between small plates, Tandoori, curries and Biryani.
An institution for a post-club feed up. You need this in your life at 3am!

Hang Dai is designed as an underground Tokyo subway. There's fine dining Chinese, a terrace and electro all night long. The menu has things like dumplings, Peking duck, brown crab, crispy pigs ears, etc.
A nice and convenient space to sit with a pint to watch the match. Everything is new and clean.

Whelans has been around for 25 years and is still a local favourite! It's a cosy, Irish pub with snugs and alternative live music every night. You can also catch trad sessions with Irish instruments such as the bódhran, spoons and uilleann pipes.
If you're looking to socialize with locals, you'll find lots of them at Blackbird.
Most pubs in Ireland serve a perfect pint of Guinness, but Devvitt's is an old reliable.
A great alternative gig venue in a particularly nice and safe part of town.
A glamorous place to go for food and drinks. Dress code: smart casual.
Inseratsbild 56
Inseratsbild 57
A very underground venue, which is only a 30 second walk from the Airbnb.

Dicey's is the most popular beer garden and nightclub in Dublin. It's based on the clubbing strip of Harcourt Street. You can sip on a €2 beer, or go upstairs to the VIP area of Krystle and crack open a bottle of Grey Goose.
Irish trad sessions are a must-do when in Ireland. O'Donoghue's is probably the best known pub for live music in Dublin.
On the high chance of it raining when you are in Dublin, I highly recommend swinging into Wigwam for a hot Irish coffee and a quick game of ping pong.
#1 bar for couples date night. Cozy and intimate, laid back and amazing cocktails.
This Yamamori branch has the nicest layout and best cocktails. Try the off menu espresso martinis, ramen, and oysters doused in kimchi sauce.
Dublin has a lack of LGBTQIA+ bars and clubs. Street 66 is a good spot though and has a small dancefloor.
The George is Dublin's oldest gay bar and definitely somewhere you want to go for a big night out. There's different levels of dancefloors, as well as live performances.
A great place to bring home crazy and unique pieces in your hand luggage.
A great place to find retro Guinness merch for bringing home in your hand luggage.
The insta worthy umbrellas outside Sams bar off South Anne Street. There's a few great bars around this area, particularly Cafe en Seine and 37 Dawson Street.

The Book of Kells is an ancient, illustrated  manuscript made by Irish monks in 800 ad. It's held in The Old Library on the grounds of Trinity College. Anyone with an interest in Celtic graphic design or calligraphy will enjoy this excursion.

The Natural History Museum (aka the Dead Zoo) is free entry and full of exotic animals as well as native Irish animals. The National Gallery of Ireland, with traditional art, is just around the corner.
The Temple Bar pub, which has more than 450 bottles of Scotch and Bourbons. Great for a selfie to spell out where you've been!
The famous Molly Malone statue! "She sells cockles and mussels, Alive-Alive-oh!"

St. Patrick's Cathedral is a monumental structure of the Protestant faith and was built in 1191. No surprise that it's the tallest and largest church in Ireland! The Dublinia museum (about Viking Dublin) is also across the road.

The Guinness Storehouse was crowned Europe's most visited tourist attraction. High above the skyline sits the Gravity bar, where you can enjoy a pint of plain. Try the Beef & Guinness Stew and Guinness Chocolate Mousse, while you're there.

A €5 tourist pass with Dublin bicycles will get you to Phoenix Park. Otherwise, the 37 bus goes from city centre. Get up early in the morning to catch the deer, sunrise and Irish mist. Dublin zoo is also here.
The Little Museum of Dublin is a people's museum. You can get a guided tour for only €8. It's a fun, educational, unique and immersive experience.

Dublin castle is a Medieval building with a governmental and royal history. It stood through the Vikings, the 1916 rebellion, changing parliaments and a major fire. Book a guide to get the full experience through storytelling.
St. Stephen's Green park is a big park on the city centre southside. You can feed the swans and ducks, roam the grounds and have a picnic on the grass.
1920s cinema in neighbouring Rathmines village. Nightly screenings and a cocktail club. Great for a rainy night - for couples or solo travellers.
Portobello is well liked for after work pints on the canal. In good weather, many Dubliners will sit here and socialize until the sun goes down.

Monkstown Castle is located 2 minutes walk from the house. The first castle here was built on a large farm by the Cistercian Monks of St Mary’s Abbey between the 14th and 15th centuries. This area was on the border of the ‘Pale’ and was frequently raided by Gaelic tribesmen such as the O’Tooles and the O’Byrnes of Wicklow. After King Henry VIII dissolved the monasteries in 1539 Monkstown passed in and out of ownership of the some of the most prominent characters and families in Irish history including the Cheevers family (a French Norman family who also owned Dalkey Castle), General Edmund Ludlow (Cromwell’s Master of the Horse in Ireland) and Michael Boyle the Lord Chancellor of Ireland. In it’s day, the castle complex had many outbuildings and was regarded as one of Dublin’s finest residences. Today however, all that remains is the gatehouse and the 3 story tower, which once formed one side of a large hall.

Located in a beautiful Art Deco building, this art house cinema has 614 seats across four screens. It also hosts the Dublin International Film Festival.

National Museum of Ireland - Decorative Arts and History

This museum has displays of furniture, silver, ceramics and glassware, as well as examples of folk life and costume, and money and weapons.

Included are artifacts such as Etruscan vases, gauntlets worn by King William at the Battle of the Boyne, a life belt and oar salvaged from the wreck of the RMS Lusitania and a pocket book carried by Wolfe Tone whilst imprisoned in the Barracks.

Step outside and straight into Smithfield Square. Also known in Irish as Margadh na Feirme, meaning "Farm Market".

Until its renovation in the early 21st Century, the square was lined with inner city 'farm yards' housing livestock.

Trendy and popular, the Dice Bar has been a hot spot in Smithfield since 2001.

Visit the historic Glasnevin Cemetery. 

The resting place of Daniel O'Connell, Charles Stewart Parnell, Éamon de Valera, Michael Collins, Charlotte Despard, Brendan Behan, John O'Leary, Luke Kelly, Billy Whelan and others.

Immerse yourself in the serenity of the nearby National Botanic Gardens.

Established in 1795, the gardens hold over 20,000 plants across nearly 20 hectares.

Learn more at the Glasnevin Cemetery Museum.

Book a tour, explore your Irish family tree, watch a historical re-enactment, hear fascinating talks and lectures or buy that perfect souvenir.
Award winning Anderson's Food Hall and cafe.

My favourite 'local', The Gravediggers pub.

Recent winner, 'Best Community Pub in Ireland', the Kavanagh family has been serving authentic Irish fare, drinks and ghost stories since 1833. 

If you like your pubs to be about atmosphere and people then you will love this perfect example of an Irish working-man's tavern.

Another local favourite - The Brian Boru bar.

There's great food, music gigs, quiz nights and a large screen for sports broadcasts.

Located on the banks of The Royal Canal it is steeped in history.   Brian Boru, High King of Ireland, camped on the site in 1014 and world-renowned writer James Joyce mentions the pub in his tour de force novel 'Ulysses'.
